{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492644","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492644"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:38:55+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:38:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1118"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1118","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1118"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.26,0.6,0.03,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1118"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104515"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1118","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1118"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1118"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86842"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"37"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1239"},{"type":"tags","id":"1487"},{"type":"tags","id":"4097"},{"type":"tags","id":"4970"},{"type":"tags","id":"4983"},{"type":"tags","id":"6400"},{"type":"tags","id":"11643"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"816"},{"type":"contributions","id":"889"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28458"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33180"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35468"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44667"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104515","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/104515"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn otherwise well 28-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-day history of gradual onset right-sided testicular pain. He denies recent trauma to the area, malaise, or urethral discharge. He had unprotected sex with a new female partner one week ago. He saw a different general practitioner two days prior who arranged scrotal ultrasound, and he has brought the ultrasound report with him today.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well and is afebrile. The right scrotum is swollen, reddened, and tender on palpation, while the left testicle is unremarkable. Elevation of the scrotum provides some pain relief, and the cremasteric reflex is present on both sides.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EScrotal ultrasonography reveals an enlarged epididymis on the right with increased blood flow.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely cause of his current problem?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Escherichia coli","Neisseria gonorrhoea","Chlamydia trachomatis","Treponema pallidum","Coxsackievirus"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis stem describes what is most consistent with a patient suffering from epididymitis. The gradual onset of pain, positive Phren\u0027s sign (elevation of the testis relieving the pain), presence of the cremasteric reflex, and history of unprotected intercourse suggest epididymitis as a diagnosis over testicular torsion. The ultrasound findings are also consistent with epididymitis rather than torsion, however, it remains an important differential diagnosis which always needs to be ruled out.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMen aged 14-35 are most commonly affected by this condition, and \u003Cstrong\u003EChlamydia trachomatis\u003C/strong\u003E is responsible for more than 50% of cases. Other pathogens to consider are \u003Cstrong\u003ENeisseria gonorrhoea\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cem\u003ETreponema pallidum\u003C/em\u003E, \u003Cem\u003ETrichomonas\u003C/em\u003E species, and \u003Cem\u003EGardnerella vaginalis\u003C/em\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhilst \u003Cstrong\u003ENeisseria gonorrhoea\u003C/strong\u003E has a slightly shorter incubation period than Chlamydia, the latter is the most commonly reported sexually transmitted infection, especially in this age group, and is more likely to be the causative organism in this case. Gonorrhoea is most commonly diagnosed in men who have sex with men, young (heterosexual) Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander people living in remote and very remote areas, and travellers returning from high prevalence areas overseas, which is not suggested in this case, making it a less likely cause in this man.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEscherichia coli\u003C/strong\u003E is a common cause of epididymitis in men over 35 years of age or in those with urinary tract abnormalities, which does not apply to this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETreponema pallidum\u003C/strong\u003E, the causative agent of syphilis, rarely causes epididymitis as a primary manifestation. Syphilis typically presents with a painless chancre at the site of inoculation, followed by systemic symptoms in secondary syphilis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECoxsackievirus \u003C/strong\u003Eis not a common cause of epididymitis. It is more commonly associated with hand, foot, and mouth disease, herpangina, and viral meningitis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Epididymitis is most commonly caused by chlamydia in sexually active males aged 14-35.","Chlamydia is the most commonly reported communicable disease in Australia.","Ultrasound findings of an enlarged epididymis with increased blood flow are indicative of epididymitis."],"references":["Srinath H. Acute scrotal pain. Aust Fam Physician. 2013 Nov;42(11):798\u2013802. Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/afp/2013/november/acute-scrotal-pain","Australian STI Management Guidelines for Use in Primary Care. Epididymo-orchitis [Internet]. Sydney: Australasian Society for HIV, Viral Hepatitis and Sexual Health Medicine. Available at: https://sti.guidelines.org.au/syndromes/epididymo-orchitis/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86842"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1118"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86842","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/86842"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-02T12:40:45+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-02T12:41:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1118"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104515"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"37","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/37"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf46","name":"Sexual Health","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"gr